<br>
Since the &quot;dues&quot; have been tossed out in favor of a community hunt -- which both suits the Dagger spirit better and will be more fiscally viable -- either of the above becomes a more useful means of sponsoring tradesfolk based on a conservative estimate of guild-fund growth.  The analysis of the two suggestions is provided via guesstimates of Dagger Night totals and full utilization of the trade sponsor program (which are both conservative and liberal respectively) and used to show the workings of the ideas.<br>
<br>
Proposal: Trade loan repayment percentage be changed from 90% to 50% of the original loan, repayable within 2 weeks. <br>
<br>
The current restrictions on these loans are: a) all outstanding loans can not exceed 1/3 of the total guild fund and b) each sponsored member can only be loaned money once per week.  <br>
<br>
With the above change to this system and assuming maximum utilization, if the guild fund is 900g and 300g is on loan, 150g will be repaid the first week leaving 750g in the guild fund.  Week 2 250g is on loan with 125g returned, 625g will remain in the guild account.  *Guesstimate* of return from Dagger Night hunt, (avg ~17g * 15 people) 250g, raising the guild fund to 875.  Week 3, 290g is on loan with 145g returned, yielding 730g. Week 4 has 250g loaned with 125 expected in return yielding 605g and add another Dagger Night guesstimate brings it up to 855g.  Net loss of 45 gold <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   using the above -guesstimates- for Daggers Nights</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  If Dagger Nights brought in 275g each, there is no loss and a little (5g) gain.<br>
<br>
It must be noted that even with adjustments in the loanable percentage, it is still possible for the guild fund to post a net loss due to the loans and the sums tradesfolk can utilize will be reduced when the guild fund is used for its other intended purposes (siege weapons, &quot;guild housing&quot;, etc).<br>
<br>
<br>
Proposal: Set aside a portion of the treasury that goes towards nothing but trade skills. The sponsored trade skill people can use this money to raise their skill, with no need to repay it. However, the amount of money set aside from the treasury can never go over 50% of the current treasury, and the money would be first come first serve. <br>
<br>
(<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   Note:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the proposal suggests 50% of the guild treasury.  This proposal <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   is being modified</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> from the above language for this example, since the stated language is not fiscally viable in the long term and I think Haemish mis--spoke (it was 4am when he posted it..then again, it'll be after 6am when I post this, so....).<br>
<br>
Modified language:  &quot;...portion of INCOME TO THE TREASURY that goes...&quot; &quot;...never go over 50% of the CURRENT INCOME TO the treasury.&quot;<br>
<br>
With the above system (modified language) if the guild treasury is 900g and Dagger Night brings in 500g gold in a given month, 250g will be available for trade folks to use to increase their skill and the guild fund will be 1150g at the end of the month.<br>
<br>
It must be noted that this system provides less for tradesfolk to use that the above system <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> based on the assumption of income used</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  However, when the guild fund is used for other intended purposes, the tradesfolk <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  continue</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to benefit from the system (whereas the &quot;loan&quot; system would decrease their funding as the guild treasury totals go down) and the guild fund itself is insulated from fluctuations in income since the portions available for tradesfolk are derived from the income itself.  Additionally, gold from the general guild fund can at times be allocated into the tradesfolk fund after prudent review of the guild's finances by the officers and if no dissention from the members -- for situations where the guild's assets far outweigh it's obligations and forecasts.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> My recommendation as Treasurer</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is the latter system (splitting the income into two budgets) as it is the most viable long-term solution for the over-all health of the guild's finances but using 30% rather than 50% <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> initially</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, with the possibility to be raised to 50% if sufficient income is being generated to meet long-term projections and more can be allocated to trades.  <br>
<br>
That is only a recommendation, however.  The decision is for the members to make. <p><table border=1 bgcolor="#161C81"width=80%>
