<br>
My main concern with the loan/repay system is that it eats directly the funds we have for other things (like sigecraft, door repair materials, etc) so that planning for these costs is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> extremely</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> hard because you have to forecast the income which...well let's just say you are making a big &quot;guess&quot; <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   You can also basically shut-down trade loans if a large part of the general fund is spent on something (guild housing, siege equip, etc).  Another small concern is, as with the dues system, at some point you have to go to someone and do the Haemish-as-Soprano routine -- at least you buy-in to that with a &quot;loan&quot;<br>
<br>
The split-income method always makes sure the general guild fund goes upward, so you can plan for expenses.  It also doens't penalize tradefolk if, say, 90% of the general guild fund is spent on guild housing -- that would essentially shut down trade loans for a time.<br>
<br>
The other benefit of the split-income method is that it's bleedin' easy to understand and for <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> any</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> member to see exactly where the guild's finances are and where they are heading -- that can't be said for the loan program running at 50%.<br>
<br>
Maybe what I'm trying to get is:  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Why</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> do folks favor one system over the other? <p><table border=1 bgcolor="#161C81"width=80%>
